SIMPLE: trance
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trance
<hw>Trance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>transe</ets>
fright, in OF. also, trance or swoon, fr. <ets>transir</ets> to chill,
benumb, to be chilled, to shiver, OF. also, to die, L.
<ets>transire</ets> to pass over, go over, pass away, cease;
<ets>trans</ets> across, over + <ets>ire</ets> to go; cf. L.
<ets>transitus</ets> a passing over. See <er>Issue</er>, and cf.
<er>Transit</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A tedious journey.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A state in which the soul seems to have passed out
of the body into another state of being, or to be rapt into visions; an
ecstasy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And he became very hungry, and would have eaten; but while they
made ready, he fell into a <qex>trance</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Acts. x.
10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My soul was ravished quite as in a <qex>trance</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A condition, often simulating
death, in which there is a total suspension of the power of voluntary
movement, with abolition of all evidences of mental activity and the
reduction to a minimum of all the vital functions so that the patient
lies still and apparently unconscious of surrounding objects, while the
pulsation of the heart and the breathing, although still present, are
almost or altogether imperceptible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He fell down in a <qex>trance</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trance</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trance
<hw>Trance</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tranced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trancing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
entrance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And three I left him <qex>tranced</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pass over or across; to traverse.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Trance</qex> the world over.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When thickest dark did <qex>trance</qex> the sky.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trance</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trance
<hw>Trance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To pass; to
travel.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tranect</ent>⟦br⟧
